Stuart Smith wrote:

 >> SkipJack is as good an algorithm as it is puported to be, then it
 >> need not be, and indeed *shouldn't* be classified.  A strong algorithm
 >> is one in which does *not* depend on one's attacker not knowing the
 >> algorithm.  If Skipjack was made public we could sit here all day
 >> debating it's relative strengths & weaknesses instead of wasting our
 >> time on DS.
 
Perhaps, rather than "security by obscurity", it's just a matter of
controlling who is allowed to use it.  IOW, if it's TOO secure, then anyone
who could re-engineer it to substitute their own, non-escrowed key, could
present some real headaches for NSA's cryptanalysis efforts.  Just a theory,
though...
